> Ohh regarding having the batch operation i.e helpful withing scripts, we need create neon db instance via drizzle-orm/neon-http and dbInstance current instance won't work and doesn't have batch operation. Checkout https://github.com/BuidlGuidl/SpeedRunEthereum-v2/pull/133#issuecomment-2817742571 for more info 

This made me think: we probably want batch operations for all our import scripts, right? Seems to be the safer (all or nothing import) and efficient way (many statements for tx)

=> To make that happen, we need `drizzle-orm/neon-http`

So there are two options:
1. Instantiate the DB on each import script using `neon-http`.
  - CONS: Repeating code (instantiating database) + we can't use repositories. Not a big deal I think.
2. Tweak PosgresClient to use `neon-http` in some case (detect if script / nextjs enviroments or env var or whatever)
  - CONS: Making it more complex

If we go with 1, I guess this PR won't make sense.

A quick and dirty example of 2:

```tsx
// Use something like this to detect if script?
const isScript = !!process.argv[1]?.includes("scripts/");
const isScript = !process.env.NEXT_RUNTIME;
```

```tsx
if (process.env.POSTGRES_URL?.includes(NEON_DB_STRING)) {
    if (isScript) {
    // Instanciate using neon-http
    } else {
    const neonPool = new NeonPool({ connectionString: process.env.POSTGRES_URL as string });
    dbInstance = drizzleNeon(neonPool, { schema, casing: "snake_case" });
   } 
}
```

Thoughts?

Thanks for the write-up Shiv, really helpful. I've been playing with it a bit.

> I think we should remove the pg library and use only @neondatabse/serverless for drivers since its drop-in replacement.

I think "drop-in" replacement means that it uses the same API as PG. So if you were using PG before to connect to Neon, you can just change it, and it works.

But for our local setup, it's not the case (We are using a classic PG database, tcp)... so it doesn't work.

I tried to use neon for it (neon, neonPool, neon-http) and all of them were giving errors while trying to run a simple import script (without transaction / batches).

Errors were:
- `fetch failed` HTTP doesn't work 
- `All attempts to open a WebSocket to connect to the database failed.` Websockets don't work

So what you were mentioning here:
> Since neondatabse has this extra feture of http, while configuring local databse instead of using normal postgreas docker, we should their neon-proxy local db setup which gives this methods as well as is more closer to prod neon databse.

It's not just an optional upgrade, we need to do it if we want to get rid of node-postgres.

I went ahead and updated the docker-compose with theirs (and it worked fine with the PG driver too). Tried to update the `postgresClient` as they suggest in https://neon.tech/guides/local-development-with-neon#connect-your-app and didn't manage to make it work ("connection refused" probably some config issue that we could figure out)

But in any case, it's super ugly... so if removing PG made us add all of this (+ we need the ws dep if we want to use websocket), it might not be worth it. eg:

```tsx
if (process.env.NODE_ENV === 'development') {
  connectionString = 'postgres://postgres:postgres@db.localtest.me:5432/main';
  neonConfig.fetchEndpoint = (host) => {
    const [protocol, port] = host === 'db.localtest.me' ? ['http', 4444] : ['https', 443];
    return `${protocol}://${host}:${port}/sql`;
  };
  const connectionStringUrl = new URL(connectionString);
  neonConfig.useSecureWebSocket = connectionStringUrl.hostname !== 'db.localtest.me';
  neonConfig.wsProxy = (host) => (host === 'db.localtest.me' ? `${host}:4444/v2` : `${host}/v2`);
}
```

