Hey Pablo, thanks for putting this together. After our conversations, I did a big refactor of the sidequest feature. Let me give some context, so @rin-st can also review.

You version was _simple_ in a sense that it was in a single file, but it was hiding a lot of complexity and had a lot of coupling.

I decided to do an architectural refactor (without getting too crazy). My main goal was to make it clear, simple, and maintainable (if we add / remove sidequests). Main pieces:

- `sideQuests/schema.ts`: The source of truth for the sidequest config (since we are not using the database to save the config, as in challenges). `SIDEQUESTS` will contain all the data that we need (e.g. link to a guide).
- `sideQuests/checks.ts`: It holds the check function for each side quest.
- `sideQuests/index.ts`: Export the main function to be used `fetchSideQuestsSnapshot`. Takes a `user` as a parameter. Changes from your approach:
  - Only saves completed sidequest to the database. I think `pending` state was a bit confusing, and we were adding a lot of unnecessary data. I think this is enough for the UI too.
  - Skip completed side quest (not sure if you had this)
  - Removed the `sidequest` object "prefix" in the new database field (`sidequests: {data}` => `{data}`)
- `sideQuests/types.ts`: just needed types.

- `onchainData/zerion.ts`: wraps Zerion API calls. (Also added some throws and console.errors)

----

To test:
- Added Zerion API KEY env var to Vercel (remove the base64 codification in the code, and just using the encoded version in the env var, as it was in the docs)
- You can create this page if you don't want to test by registering all the time:

```ts
// app/sidequest/page.tsx
import { getUserByAddress } from "~~/services/database/repositories/users";
import { fetchSideQuestsSnapshot } from "~~/services/sideQuests";

export default async function SideQuestsPage() {
  // TODO: Replace with the user you like that exist in the database.
  const user = await getUserByAddress("0xB4F53bd85c00EF22946d24Ae26BC38Ac64F5E7B1");
  if (!user) {
    throw new Error("User not found");
  }
  const sideQuests = await fetchSideQuestsSnapshot(user);
  return <pre>{JSON.stringify(sideQuests, null, 2)}</pre>;
}
```

e.g. If you register or refresh (with no previous ENS data on the DB, but the address has ens) you'll get.

```
{
  "usedL2": {
    "id": "usedL2",
    "completedAt": "2025-08-29T08:29:24.380Z"
  },
  "sentMainnetTx": {
    "id": "sentMainnetTx",
    "completedAt": "2025-08-29T08:29:24.502Z"
  }
}
```

`ens` field will be filled, but not computed

When you need to do something like this, usually "lookup maps" / objects are a better option (more readable, easier to extend, plays better with TS, etc)

Since we are moving the "enum" (from `database/types` to `utils/challenges`), you could do something like:

```tsx
export const SKILL_LEVELS = {
  BEGINNER: "Beginner",
  INTERMEDIATE: "Intermediate",
  ADVANCED: "Advanced",
} as const;

export type SkillLevel = (typeof SKILL_LEVELS)[keyof typeof SKILL_LEVELS];
```
